Our project AirGuard powered by TEMPO is designed to transform NASAâ€™s satellite data into something people and institutions can actually use in their daily decisions. The idea is to build a system that combines TEMPO observations with ground based networks like OpenAQ AirNow and Pandora together with weather data from NOAA and OpenWeatherMap. Instead of leaving communities with raw numbers we forecast local air quality for the next 6 to 24 hours validate the results using portable IoT robotics and then deliver the information through two main applications. The first is a web platform for schools hospitals and municipalities where they can monitor conditions and manage alerts. The second is a mobile app for citizens that shows AQI provides health tips and sends real time notifications. We gather data from space missions like Kepler, K2, and TESS, then carefully clean and organize it to spotlight important details, like how long a planet takes to orbit its star or how much light it blocks during a transit. 405,7833,Beyond unseen,4,true,false,https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1P-Xe1UPLwiAnD71wA553EvoqUAP-BjdN?usp=drive_link,https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1UXES2nOMlqXXH7qi_OiekLtSaXby0WIj?usp=drive_link,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,1696,7708,Jana Ahmed Abosrea Fathi,janaahmed1955@gmail.com,01150151973,17,female,6 Ø´ Ø¹Ø¨Ø¯ Ø§Ù„Ù…Ù†Ø¹Ù… Ø¹Ø¨Ø¯Ø§Ù„Ø³Ù„Ø§Ù… -Ø·Ø±Ø©- Ø§Ù„Ù…Ø¹Ø§Ø¯Ù‰,false,New Cairo STEM School,1,team_lead,null,null,30804260102105,2025-09-27 08:49:20,16,Through the Radar Looking Glass: Revealing Earth Processes with SAR,Encourages innovative use of SAR technology to monitor and reveal complex earth surface processes and changes.,Our team, Beyond Unseen, is exploring the critical importance of Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) in monitoring natural disasters, with a focus on floods and wildfires. Unlike optical imagery, which depends on daylight and clear skies, SAR can penetrate clouds, smoke, and darkness. In flood events, SAR reveals inundated areas hidden beneath clouds, supporting faster relief planning. During wildfires, it can capture structural changes in vegetation even when thick smoke blocks optical sensors. 424,9033,TrashtoMars,4,false,false,https://docs.google.com/document/d/1xpj_Vm1cUOGtT9VbZVVt2hXLXtZnHElSIrmyFzyaOTQ/edit?usp=sharing,https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1r8Q48XsFYtztCPg9o4_Npr4cejcgNMpf?usp=sharing,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,1779,4484,Mina Sameh,sos229072@gmail.com,01027382269,17,male,Cairo, Nasr City,false,St. Fatima Language School El hegaz,1,team_lead,null,null,30806270104656,2025-09-27 09:00:15,14,SpaceTrash Hack: Revolutionizing Recycling on Mars,Seeks solutions for effective recycling and waste reduction strategies in Martian habitats or missions.,Trash2Mars is an automated recycling system that transforms inorganic waste from Mars missions into vital resources. In a three-year mission, an eight-person crew generates over 12,600 kg of plastics, metals, textiles, and glass. Instead of storing or discarding this waste, Trash2Mars converts it into structural blocks, shielding, and repair materials.

Plastics and textiles are processed through microwave pyrolysis, producing carbon residues and backup fuels. Metals, glass, and ceramics are melted in an electric smelter and blended with Martian regolith to create radiation-resistant panels and tiles.

By turning waste into construction and protection, Trash2Mars eliminates hazards, reduces dependence on Earth, and supports astronaut survival with a sustainable closed-loop model: Waste + Regolith = Life Support.,null,1,onsite,null,Mina Sameh, Basmala Elgohary, Mariam Fayeq Gabriel, Esraa Samir Ahmed,https://adminpanel.spaceappscairo.com/storage/7039/Trash2Mars.PNG,https://adminpanel.spaceappscairo.com/storage/7039/conversions/Trash2Mars-thumb.jpg,https://adminpanel.spaceappscairo.com/storage/7039/conversions/Trash2Mars-preview.jpg,2025-09-27 09:00:15
